Removing ? from columns¶
In [5]:
# There are no nulls as such but there are ? in place of null data as viewed from file.
# Let's deal with those columns first

columns_having_mark = []
for col in df_train.columns:
    if df_train[col].dtype == 'object':
        mask = df_train[col].apply(lambda x: '?' in x)
        columns_having_mark.append(col if mask.sum() > 0 else None)

columns_having_mark = [item for item in columns_having_mark if item is not None]
In [6]:
# Removing the rows having ? in workclass column

clean_df_train = df_train[df_train[columns_having_mark[0]].astype(str).str.contains(r'\?') == False]
In [7]:
# Performing the same for other columns

clean_df_train = clean_df_train[clean_df_train[columns_having_mark[1]].astype(str).str.contains(r'\?') == False]
clean_df_train = clean_df_train[clean_df_train[columns_having_mark[2]].astype(str).str.contains(r'\?') == False]

In [9]:
clean_df_train = clean_df_train.reset_index(drop=True)

Some features are categorical and some are numerical as we have seen. Now even though decision tree and random forest can work with it, but sklearn is not built to work with categorical data. We have to transform the categorical data into numerical one.

This is the accuracy with overfitted model. Now let's try and apply pruning and see the outcome -

In [21]:
clf_dt_prun = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, ccp_alpha=0.001)
# ccp_alpha is the pruning parameter and 0.001 worked best for the data

clf_dt_prun.fit(train_input, train_target)

plt.figure(figsize=(14,6))
plot_tree(clf_dt_prun, filled = True)
plt.show()
In [22]:
